<dl id="n38169d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38169d">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38169d"> 169(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Shabti figures <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n38169d"><li>FW 25.02 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n38169d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n38169d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n38169d">MS BL 47475-102</ms> </li><li>JJA 44:280 <a name="ad5y" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#ad5y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad5.htm#n38169d">Draft: I.1&sect;1.5</a>+/2.5+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The text of Chapter VI was cut on figures made of stone, wood, etc.,(<i>ushabtiu</i>), which were placed in the tomb, and when the deceased recited it these figures became alive and did everything he wished. The <mark><i>shabti</i> figure</mark> took the place of the human funerary sacrifice which was common all over Egypt before the general adoption of the cult of Osiris under the XIIth dynasty. <small> E.A. Wallis Budge, <a name="BOD2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BOD2"><cite title="source">The Book of the Dead</cite></a> (1920) 36</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
